{tier:2,icon:"📋",name:"Interfaces",build:()=>`
<div class="lesson-header">
  <div class="tier-pill" style="background:rgba(245,158,11,0.1);color:#f59e0b">Tier 3 — Functions &amp; Classes</div>
  <h1>📋 Interfaces</h1>
  <p>An interface is a contract — it says "anything that implements me MUST have these methods." Interfaces let completely different objects be treated the same way.</p>
  <div class="badges"><span class="badge new">★ interface</span><span class="badge new">★ implements</span><span class="badge new">★ IDamageable</span><span class="badge new">★ multiple interfaces</span><span class="badge new">★ GetComponent&lt;IInterface&gt;</span></div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>🧠 Interface vs Abstract Class</h2>
  <table class="ctable">
    <tr><th></th><th>Interface</th><th>Abstract Class</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Can have code?</strong></td><td>No body (only signatures) *</td><td>Yes — can have real methods</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Multiple?</strong></td><td>✅ One class can implement many</td><td>❌ Only one base class allowed</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Constructors?</strong></td><td>❌ No</td><td>✅ Yes</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Fields?</strong></td><td>❌ No instance fields</td><td>✅ Yes</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Best for</strong></td><td>Capabilities (can take damage, can interact)</td><td>Shared behaviour (all enemies share this)</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="note-box">* In modern C# (8+), interfaces CAN have default method bodies, but in Unity development it's best practice to keep them as pure contracts.</div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>💻 Defining and Implementing an Interface</h2>
  <pre><span class="cm">// Define an interface — starts with I by convention</span>
<span class="kw">public interface</span> <span class="ty">IDamageable</span>
{
    <span class="ty">int</span>  Health  { <span class="kw">get</span>; }           <span class="cm">// read-only property required</span>
    <span class="kw">void</span> <span class="fn">TakeDamage</span>(<span class="ty">int</span> amount);    <span class="cm">// method required</span>
    <span class="kw">void</span> <span class="fn">Die</span>();                       <span class="cm">// method required</span>
}

<span class="cm">// A Player that is damageable</span>
<span class="kw">public class</span> <span class="ty">Player</span> : <span class="uk">MonoBehaviour</span>, <span class="ty">IDamageable</span>
{
    [<span class="uk">SerializeField</span>] <span class="kw">private</span> <span class="ty">int</span> maxHealth = <span class="num">100</span>;
    <span class="kw">private</span> <span class="ty">int</span> currentHealth;

    <span class="kw">void</span> <span class="fn">Start</span>() { currentHealth = maxHealth; }

    <span class="kw">public</span> <span class="ty">int</span>  Health => currentHealth;   <span class="cm">// satisfies IDamageable.Health</span>

    <span class="kw">public void</span> <span class="fn">TakeDamage</span>(<span class="ty">int</span> amount)
    {
        currentHealth -= amount;
        <span class="kw">if</span> (currentHealth &lt;= <span class="num">0</span>) <span class="fn">Die</span>();
    }

    <span class="kw">public void</span> <span class="fn">Die</span>()
    {
        <span class="uk">Debug</span>.<span class="fn">Log</span>(<span class="str">"Player died!"</span>);
        <span class="uk">Destroy</span>(gameObject);
    }
}

<span class="cm">// An Enemy that is ALSO damageable — totally different class, same interface</span>
<span class="kw">public class</span> <span class="ty">Enemy</span> : <span class="uk">MonoBehaviour</span>, <span class="ty">IDamageable</span>
{
    <span class="kw">private</span> <span class="ty">int</span> currentHealth = <span class="num">50</span>;
    <span class="kw">public</span> <span class="ty">int</span> Health => currentHealth;

    <span class="kw">public void</span> <span class="fn">TakeDamage</span>(<span class="ty">int</span> amount)
    {
        currentHealth -= amount;
        <span class="kw">if</span> (currentHealth &lt;= <span class="num">0</span>) <span class="fn">Die</span>();
    }

    <span class="kw">public void</span> <span class="fn">Die</span>() { <span class="uk">Destroy</span>(gameObject); }
}</pre>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>🎮 Using Interfaces in Unity — GetComponent</h2>
  <pre><span class="cm">// The power: a bullet doesn't need to know if it hit a Player or Enemy
// It just checks if the target is IDamageable</span>

<span class="kw">public class</span> <span class="ty">Bullet</span> : <span class="uk">MonoBehaviour</span>
{
    <span class="kw">public</span> <span class="ty">int</span> damage = <span class="num">25</span>;

    <span class="kw">void</span> <span class="fn">OnTriggerEnter</span>(<span class="ty">Collider</span> other)
    {
        <span class="cm">// GetComponent works with interfaces!</span>
        <span class="ty">IDamageable</span> target = other.<span class="fn">GetComponent</span>&lt;<span class="ty">IDamageable</span>&gt;();
        <span class="kw">if</span> (target != <span class="kw">null</span>)
        {
            target.<span class="fn">TakeDamage</span>(damage);  <span class="cm">// works for Player OR Enemy!</span>
        }
        <span class="uk">Destroy</span>(gameObject);
    }
}

<span class="cm">// Multiple interfaces on one class</span>
<span class="kw">public interface</span> <span class="ty">IInteractable</span>
{
    <span class="ty">string</span> InteractText { <span class="kw">get</span>; }
    <span class="kw">void</span> <span class="fn">Interact</span>(<span class="ty">Player</span> player);
}

<span class="kw">public interface</span> <span class="ty">IPickupable</span>
{
    <span class="kw">void</span> <span class="fn">PickUp</span>(<span class="ty">Player</span> player);
}

<span class="cm">// A Health Potion can be interacted with AND picked up</span>
<span class="kw">public class</span> <span class="ty">HealthPotion</span> : <span class="uk">MonoBehaviour</span>, <span class="ty">IInteractable</span>, <span class="ty">IPickupable</span>
{
    <span class="kw">public</span> <span class="ty">string</span> InteractText => <span class="str">"Press E to drink"</span>;
    <span class="kw">public void</span> <span class="fn">Interact</span>(<span class="ty">Player</span> p) { <span class="fn">PickUp</span>(p); }
    <span class="kw">public void</span> <span class="fn">PickUp</span>(<span class="ty">Player</span> p)   { p.<span class="fn">Heal</span>(<span class="num">50</span>); <span class="uk">Destroy</span>(gameObject); }
}</pre>

  <div class="unity-box">🎮 <strong>Common Unity interfaces (built-in):</strong><br>
  <code>IPointerClickHandler</code> — UI click events<br>
  <code>IPointerEnterHandler</code> — UI hover<br>
  <code>IDragHandler</code> — UI drag<br>
  <code>IComparable&lt;T&gt;</code> — sorting (for leaderboards etc.)</div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>🔍 Checking at Runtime</h2>
  <pre><span class="cm">// Check if an object implements an interface without crashing</span>
<span class="ty">IDamageable</span> dmg = other.<span class="fn">GetComponent</span>&lt;<span class="ty">IDamageable</span>&gt;();
<span class="kw">if</span> (dmg != <span class="kw">null</span>) dmg.<span class="fn">TakeDamage</span>(<span class="num">10</span>);

<span class="cm">// OR: pattern matching (C# 7+, cleaner)</span>
<span class="kw">if</span> (other.<span class="fn">TryGetComponent</span>&lt;<span class="ty">IDamageable</span>&gt;(<span class="kw">out</span> <span class="ty">IDamageable</span> target))
{
    target.<span class="fn">TakeDamage</span>(<span class="num">10</span>);
}

<span class="cm">// is keyword check</span>
<span class="kw">if</span> (someObject <span class="kw">is</span> <span class="ty">IDamageable</span> d)
{
    d.<span class="fn">TakeDamage</span>(<span class="num">10</span>);
}</pre>
</div>

${Q([
  {q:"What is an interface in C#?",opts:["A type of class","A contract that says 'implementors MUST have these methods/properties'","A way to inherit from multiple classes","A Unity component"],ans:1,explain:"An interface defines a contract — a list of method and property signatures that any implementing class must provide. It has no implementation itself, just the signatures."},
  {q:"How many interfaces can one class implement?",opts:["Only one","Only two","As many as needed","None — interfaces are optional"],ans:2,explain:"A class can implement as many interfaces as needed: public class Door : MonoBehaviour, IInteractable, IOpenable, IDestructible. This is why interfaces are more flexible than inheritance for capabilities."},
