])}
`},

{tier:4,icon:"🎭",name:"Animator & Animations",build:()=>`
<div class="lesson-header">
  <div class="tier-pill" style="background:rgba(244,114,182,0.1);color:#f472b6">Tier 5 — Unity Gameplay</div>
  <h1>🎭 Animator, Animation Clips &amp; the State Machine</h1>
  <p>Animation in Unity has three layers: the <strong>clip</strong> (the recorded motion), the <strong>Animator Controller</strong> (the state machine that decides which clip plays), and the <strong>Animator component</strong> (attached to the object). You need all three.</p>
  <div class="badges"><span class="badge unity">★ Animation Clip</span><span class="badge unity">★ Animator Controller</span><span class="badge unity">★ State Machine</span><span class="badge unity">★ Parameters</span><span class="badge unity">★ Transitions</span></div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>🧠 The Three Pieces — How They Connect</h2>
  <table class="ctable">
    <tr><th>Piece</th><th>What it is</th><th>How to create it</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Animation Clip</strong> (.anim)</td><td>Records property changes over time — position, rotation, colour, etc. One clip = one action (walk, idle, jump)</td><td>Window → Animation → Animation → Create</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Animator Controller</strong> (.controller)</td><td>The state machine — decides <em>which</em> clip plays and <em>when</em> to switch between them based on parameters</td><td>Project panel → right-click → Create → Animator Controller</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Animator Component</strong></td><td>Sits on the GameObject. Plays what the Controller tells it to</td><td>Add Component → Animator (drag your Controller into its Controller slot)</td></tr>
  </table>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>🎬 Step 1 — Record an Animation Clip</h2>
  <pre><span class="cm">// ── How to record a clip in Unity ──────────────────────────────

// 1. Select the GameObject you want to animate in the Hierarchy
//    (e.g. your Player Capsule)

// 2. Open the Animation window:
//    Window → Animation → Animation   (or Ctrl+6)

// 3. Click "Create" in the Animation window
//    Choose where to save it (your Animations/ folder)
//    Name it something like "PlayerIdle" or "PlayerWalk"
//    Unity automatically creates an Animator Controller too!

// 4. Click the red Record button (●) in the Animation window
//    Now ANY changes you make to the object are recorded as keyframes:
//    - Move the scrubber to frame 10 → move the object → keyframe added
//    - Move scrubber to frame 30 → move back → keyframe added
//    - Unity interpolates between keyframes automatically

// 5. Click Record again to stop recording

// 6. Press Play in the Animation window to preview the clip
//    The object should animate back and forth

// ── To create MORE clips for the same object ──────────────────
// In the Animation window, click the clip name dropdown (top left)
// "Create New Clip" → name it (e.g. "PlayerRun")
// Record new keyframes for this clip
// Both clips are now in the Animator Controller</span></pre>
  <div class="tip-box">💡 You can animate <strong>any property</strong> — Transform (position, rotation, scale), Material colour, light intensity, sprite, UI alpha. If it's in the Inspector, it can be keyframed.</div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>🔄 Step 2 — The Animator State Machine</h2>
  <p>Open the Animator window: <strong>Window → Animation → Animator</strong>. You'll see a graph of states connected by arrows.</p>
  <pre><span class="cm">// ── What you see in the Animator window ────────────────────────

// States (coloured boxes):
//   "Entry" → grey — the starting point, connects to your default state
//   "Any State" → grey — can transition FROM here to any state at any time
//   "Exit" → grey — exits the animation layer entirely
//   Your clips (green/orange) — each clip is one state

// Default state (orange):
//   The state that plays first when the object is enabled.
//   Right-click a state → "Set as Layer Default State"

// Transitions (arrows between states):
//   An arrow from StateA to StateB = "under these conditions, switch"
//   Click an arrow to see its conditions in the Inspector

// ── How to add a transition ─────────────────────────────────────
// Right-click the source state → "Make Transition"
// Click the destination state → an arrow appears
// Click the arrow → in the Inspector, add a Condition (parameter + value)

// ── How to add a parameter ──────────────────────────────────────
// In the Animator window, top-left: click the "Parameters" tab
// Click the + button:
//   Bool   → for persistent states (isRunning, isGrounded)
//   Trigger → for one-shot events (Jump, Attack, Die)
//   Float  → for blend trees (movement speed)
//   Int    → for state selection (weapon type)

// ── Example state machine for a platformer ──────────────────────
// States: Idle → Walk → Jump → Fall → Land
// Parameters:
//   float Speed    (0 = idle, >0.1 = walking)
//   trigger Jump
//   bool  IsGrounded
//
// Transitions:
//   Idle → Walk:  Speed > 0.1
//   Walk → Idle:  Speed < 0.1
//   Any State → Jump: Jump (trigger)
//   Jump → Fall:  vertical velocity < 0
//   Fall → Land:  IsGrounded == true</span></pre>
  <div class="note-box">⚠️ <strong>Has Exit Time:</strong> By default, new transitions have "Has Exit Time" checked — this means the transition waits for the clip to finish before switching. For gameplay-responsive animations (jump, attack) UNCHECK this so transitions are instant.</div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>💻 Step 3 — Controlling Animations from Code</h2>
  <pre><span class="cm">// Scripts/PlayerAnimator.cs — attach alongside PlayerController</span>
<span class="kw">using</span> UnityEngine;

<span class="kw">public class</span> <span class="ty">PlayerAnimator</span> : <span class="uk">MonoBehaviour</span>
{
    <span class="kw">private</span> <span class="ty">Animator</span>  anim;
    <span class="kw">private</span> <span class="ty">Rigidbody</span> rb;

    <span class="kw">void</span> <span class="fn">Awake</span>()
    {
        anim = <span class="fn">GetComponent</span>&lt;<span class="ty">Animator</span>&gt;();
        rb   = <span class="fn">GetComponent</span>&lt;<span class="ty">Rigidbody</span>&gt;();
    }

    <span class="kw">void</span> <span class="fn">Update</span>()
    {
        <span class="cm">// Float parameter drives a blend tree (idle ↔ walk ↔ run)</span>
        <span class="ty">float</span> speed = <span class="kw">new</span> <span class="ty">Vector3</span>(rb.velocity.x, <span class="num">0</span>, rb.velocity.z).magnitude;
        anim.<span class="fn">SetFloat</span>(<span class="str">"Speed"</span>, speed);

        <span class="cm">// Bool parameter — true while moving</span>
        anim.<span class="fn">SetBool</span>(<span class="str">"IsRunning"</span>, speed > <span class="num">0.1f</span>);

        <span class="cm">// Trigger — fires once on keypress</span>
        <span class="kw">if</span> (<span class="uk">Input</span>.<span class="fn">GetKeyDown</span>(<span class="uk">KeyCode</span>.Space))
            anim.<span class="fn">SetTrigger</span>(<span class="str">"Jump"</span>);
    }

    <span class="cm">// Called externally (e.g. from IDamageable.Die())</span>
    <span class="kw">public void</span> <span class="fn">PlayHit</span>()   => anim.<span class="fn">SetTrigger</span>(<span class="str">"Hit"</span>);
    <span class="kw">public void</span> <span class="fn">PlayDeath</span>() => anim.<span class="fn">SetTrigger</span>(<span class="str">"Die"</span>);
}</pre>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>🌀 Blend Trees — Smooth Speed-Based Transitions</h2>
  <pre><span class="cm">// A Blend Tree blends between clips based on a float value.
// Perfect for: idle → walk → run (based on movement speed)

// ── How to create a Blend Tree ──────────────────────────────────
// In the Animator window:
//   right-click empty space → Create State → From New Blend Tree
//   Double-click the Blend Tree to enter it
//   Inspector → Parameter: choose your "Speed" float

// ── Add clips to the blend tree ────────────────────────────────
// Inspector → click + → Add Motion Field
//   Threshold 0.0 → drag Idle clip
//   Threshold 0.5 → drag Walk clip
//   Threshold 1.0 → drag Run clip
// Check "Automate Thresholds" for Unity to space them evenly

// ── Result ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Speed 0.0  → plays Idle
// Speed 0.5  → blends Walk 50% / Run 50%
// Speed 1.0  → plays Run
// All transitions are perfectly smooth — no abrupt cuts</span></pre>
  <div class="tip-box">💡 Blend Trees are the professional way to handle movement animations. Instead of 3 separate transitions between idle/walk/run, one float value smoothly blends all three.</div>
</div>

${Q([
  {q:"What are the three pieces needed for animation in Unity?",opts:["Rigidbody, Collider, Script","Animation Clip, Animator Controller, Animator Component","Sprite, Material, Shader","Prefab, Blueprint, Asset"],ans:1,explain:"Clip = the recorded motion data. Animator Controller = the state machine deciding which clip plays. Animator Component = attached to the GameObject, plays what the controller says. All three must be connected."},
  {q:"You want a jump animation that plays instantly when Space is pressed — not after the current clip finishes. What do you uncheck?",opts:["Loop Time","Has Exit Time","Apply Root Motion","Bake Into Pose"],ans:1,explain:"'Has Exit Time' makes Unity wait for the current clip to finish before transitioning. For responsive gameplay actions (jump, attack), uncheck it so the transition fires immediately when the condition is met."},
  {q:"What type of Animator parameter would you use for a sprint that should keep playing as long as the player holds Shift?",opts:["Trigger","Bool","Float","Int"],ans:1,explain:"Bool stays true until you set it false — perfect for persistent states like isRunning, isCrouching, isGrounded. Trigger only fires for one frame then auto-resets itself."},
  {q:"What does a Blend Tree do that regular transitions cannot?",opts:["Plays multiple clips simultaneously on different bones","Smoothly interpolates between clips based on a float value — no sharp cuts","Allows triggers to work on multiple states","Connects the Animator to the Rigidbody"],ans:1,explain:"A Blend Tree takes a float (like speed 0–1) and smoothly blends between clips at different threshold values. Regular transitions snap from one clip to another. Blend Trees are the standard approach for movement animations."},
  {q:"Parameter name 'isRunning' in code, 'IsRunning' in the Animator. What happens?",opts:["Unity auto-corrects case","They are treated as two different parameters — the code does nothing","A compile error occurs","Both work identically"],ans:1,explain:"Parameter names are case-sensitive. 'isRunning' and 'IsRunning' are completely different parameters. The SetBool call silently does nothing if the name doesn't match exactly. Always copy-paste names from the Animator window."},
])}

${FIB("Complete the animator setup for a player movement system:",
`<span class="cm">// Awake: cache references</span>
<span class="kw">private</span> ${blank('Animator',9)} anim;
anim = ${blank('GetComponent',13)}&lt;<span class="ty">Animator</span>&gt;();

<span class="cm">// Update: drive a blend tree with movement speed</span>
<span class="ty">float</span> speed = rb.velocity.${blank('magnitude',10)};
anim.${blank('SetFloat',9)}(<span class="str">"Speed"</span>, speed);

<span class="cm">// One-shot jump animation</span>
