<div class="section">
  <h2>🧠 Lua Data Types</h2>
  <table class="ctable">
    <tr><th>Type</th><th>Example</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>number</code></td><td><code>local score = 10</code></td><td>All numbers in Lua are floats under the hood</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>string</code></td><td><code>local name = "Alex"</code></td><td>Use " or ' — both work</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>boolean</code></td><td><code>local alive = true</code></td><td>Only <code>true</code> or <code>false</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>nil</code></td><td><code>local x = nil</code></td><td>Means "nothing" / undefined</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>table</code></td><td><code>local t = {}</code></td><td>Arrays AND dictionaries — covered in Tier 3</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>function</code></td><td><code>local f = function() end</code></td><td>Functions are first-class values</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="lua-box">💡 <strong>Always use <code>local</code></strong> when declaring variables. Without it, the variable becomes global — accessible everywhere, which causes hard-to-find bugs.</div>
