{tier:1,icon:"⚖️",name:"If / Then / Else",build:()=>`
<div class="lesson-header">
  <div class="tier-pill" style="background:rgba(244,114,182,0.1);color:#f472b6">Tier 2 — Control Flow</div>
  <h1>⚖️ If / Then / Else</h1>
  <p>Make decisions in your Lua code. Control which code runs based on conditions.</p>
  <div class="badges"><span class="badge new">★ if/then/else</span><span class="badge new">★ elseif</span><span class="badge new">★ comparison operators</span><span class="badge new">★ and/or/not</span></div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>💻 If / Then / Else Syntax</h2>
  <pre><span class="kw">local</span> health = <span class="num">75</span>

<span class="kw">if</span> health &gt; <span class="num">50</span> <span class="kw">then</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(<span class="str">"Healthy"</span>)
<span class="kw">elseif</span> health &gt; <span class="num">25</span> <span class="kw">then</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(<span class="str">"Low health!"</span>)
<span class="kw">else</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(<span class="str">"Critical!"</span>)
<span class="kw">end</span>   <span class="cm">-- Lua uses "end" to close blocks, NOT {}</span></pre>

  <table class="ctable" style="margin-top:10px">
    <tr><th>Operator</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>==</code></td><td>Equal to</td><td><code>health == 100</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>~=</code></td><td>NOT equal (use ~= not !=)</td><td><code>name ~= "enemy"</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&gt;</code> <code>&lt;</code></td><td>Greater / Less than</td><td><code>score &gt; 0</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&gt;=</code> <code>&lt;=</code></td><td>Greater/less or equal</td><td><code>lives &lt;= 0</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>and</code></td><td>Both must be true</td><td><code>alive and hasKey</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>or</code></td><td>At least one true</td><td><code>won or quit</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>not</code></td><td>Invert boolean</td><td><code>not isGameOver</code></td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="note-box">⚠️ In Lua, not equal is <code>~=</code> (tilde-equals), NOT <code>!=</code>. This is unique to Lua!</div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>🔀 Truthy / Falsy in Lua</h2>
  <pre><span class="cm">-- In Lua, ONLY false and nil are falsy.</span>
<span class="cm">-- Everything else (including 0 and "") is TRUTHY!</span>

<span class="kw">if</span> <span class="num">0</span> <span class="kw">then</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(<span class="str">"0 is truthy in Lua!"</span>)    <span class="cm">-- this RUNS!</span>
<span class="kw">end</span>

<span class="kw">if</span> <span class="str">""</span> <span class="kw">then</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(<span class="str">"Empty string is truthy!"</span>)  <span class="cm">-- this also RUNS!</span>
<span class="kw">end</span>

<span class="kw">if</span> <span class="kw">nil</span> <span class="kw">then</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(<span class="str">"Never runs"</span>)             <span class="cm">-- nil is falsy</span>
<span class="kw">end</span>

<span class="cm">-- Lua trick: default value using 'or'</span>
<span class="kw">local</span> name = playerName <span class="kw">or</span> <span class="str">"Guest"</span>  <span class="cm">-- use "Guest" if playerName is nil</span></pre>

  <div class="note-box">⚠️ <strong>0 is truthy in Lua!</strong> This surprises people from other languages. Only <code>false</code> and <code>nil</code> are falsy in Lua.</div>
</div>

<div class="mistake-box">
  <h3>⚠️ Common Mistakes</h3>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div><div class="ml bad">✗ WRONG</div><div class="wc">if score != 0 then  -- != not valid in Lua</div></div>
    <div><div class="ml good">✓ RIGHT</div><div class="rc">if score ~= 0 then  -- ~= is "not equal"</div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div><div class="ml bad">✗ WRONG</div><div class="wc">if health > 0 {   -- no braces in Lua!</div></div>
    <div><div class="ml good">✓ RIGHT</div><div class="rc">if health > 0 then ... end</div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="mistake-item">
    <div><div class="ml bad">✗ WRONG</div><div class="wc">if isAlive == true then  -- redundant</div></div>
    <div><div class="ml good">✓ RIGHT</div><div class="rc">if isAlive then  -- cleaner</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

${Q([
  {q:"How do you write 'not equal' in Lua?",opts:["!=","<>","~=","=/="],ans:2,explain:"Lua uses ~= for not-equal. Most other languages use != but Lua is different. ~= is unique to Lua."},
  {q:"In Lua, what values are considered FALSY?",opts:["0 and false","false and nil","0, false, and nil","false, nil, and empty string"],ans:1,explain:"Only false and nil are falsy in Lua. This is different from JavaScript! 0, empty string, and empty table are all truthy in Lua."},
  {q:"What keyword closes an if block in Lua?",opts:["}","endif","end","close"],ans:2,explain:"Lua uses 'end' to close all blocks — if, for, while, function. There are no curly braces {} in Lua."},
  {q:"What does <code>local name = playerName or \"Guest\"</code> do?",opts:["Crashes if playerName is nil","Uses 'Guest' if playerName is nil or false","Always uses 'Guest'","Compares the two values"],ans:1,explain:"This is a common Lua idiom. 'or' returns the first truthy value — so if playerName is nil (falsy), it returns 'Guest'. It's a clean way to set defaults."},
  {q:"Which keyword is used instead of 'else if' in Lua?",opts:["elif","else if","elseif","elsif"],ans:2,explain:"Lua uses 'elseif' (one word, no space). C# uses 'else if' (two words). Don't put a space in Lua's elseif!"},
  {q:"What is <code>not (health <= 0)</code> equivalent to?",opts:["health < 0","health == 0","health > 0","health >= 0"],ans:2,explain:"not inverts the condition. not (health <= 0) means 'health is NOT less than or equal to 0', which is the same as 'health > 0'."},
])}

${FIB("Complete the health system if/then/else:",
`<span class="kw">local</span> health = <span class="num">30</span>

<span class="kw">if</span> health ${blank('<=',3)} <span class="num">0</span> ${blank('then',5)}
    <span class="rb">print</span>(<span class="str">"Game Over!"</span>)
${blank('elseif',7)} health < <span class="num">25</span> then
    <span class="fn">warn</span>(<span class="str">"Critical health!"</span>)
${blank('elseif',7)} health < <span class="num">50</span> then
    <span class="fn">warn</span>(<span class="str">"Low health"</span>)
${blank('else',5)}
    <span class="rb">print</span>(<span class="str">"Healthy"</span>)
${blank('end',4)}`,
['<=','then','elseif','elseif','else','end'])}

${BUG("This score check has a bug — it never prints anything when score is 10:",
`local score = 10

if score != 0 then
    print("You have a score!")
end`,
["score should be a string","<code>!=</code> is not valid Lua — use <code>~=</code>","<code>then</code> keyword is missing","print is spelled wrong"],1,
"Lua uses ~= for 'not equal', not !=. != is from C-style languages (C#, JavaScript). The correct line is: if score ~= 0 then")}

${CHALLENGES([
  "Write a grade calculator: ask for a score using a variable, print A/B/C/D/F using if/elseif/else.",
  "Build a day/night check: if hour >= 6 and hour < 18, print 'Daytime', else 'Nighttime'.",
  "Write a password validator: check length >= 8 AND not equal to 'password'.",
  "Use the 'or' trick to set default values for 3 variables that might be nil.",
  "Write a damage calculator: if the player has a shield (boolean), halve the damage; if critical hit (boolean), double it.",
])}
`},

