{tier:1,icon:"🔁",name:"Loops",build:()=>`
<div class="lesson-header">
  <div class="tier-pill" style="background:rgba(244,114,182,0.1);color:#f472b6">Tier 2 — Control Flow</div>
  <h1>🔁 Loops</h1>
  <p>Repeat code efficiently. Lua has three loop types: numeric for, generic for, and while. Plus repeat-until.</p>
  <div class="badges"><span class="badge new">★ numeric for</span><span class="badge new">★ while / repeat</span><span class="badge new">★ ipairs / pairs</span><span class="badge new">★ break</span></div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>💻 Numeric For Loop</h2>
  <pre><span class="cm">-- for variable = start, stop, step do</span>
<span class="kw">for</span> i = <span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">5</span> <span class="kw">do</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(i)   <span class="cm">-- 1, 2, 3, 4, 5</span>
<span class="kw">end</span>

<span class="cm">-- With step</span>
<span class="kw">for</span> i = <span class="num">0</span>, <span class="num">10</span>, <span class="num">2</span> <span class="kw">do</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(i)   <span class="cm">-- 0, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10</span>
<span class="kw">end</span>

<span class="cm">-- Counting down</span>
<span class="kw">for</span> i = <span class="num">10</span>, <span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">-1</span> <span class="kw">do</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(i)   <span class="cm">-- 10, 9, 8 ... 1</span>
<span class="kw">end</span>

<span class="cm">-- Loop over array with index</span>
<span class="kw">local</span> weapons = {<span class="str">"Sword"</span>, <span class="str">"Bow"</span>, <span class="str">"Staff"</span>}
<span class="kw">for</span> i = <span class="num">1</span>, #weapons <span class="kw">do</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(i, weapons[i])
<span class="kw">end</span></pre>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>💻 Generic For, While, and Repeat</h2>
  <pre><span class="cm">-- Generic for with ipairs (array tables)</span>
<span class="kw">for</span> i, v <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="fn">ipairs</span>(weapons) <span class="kw">do</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(i, v)
<span class="kw">end</span>

<span class="cm">-- Generic for with pairs (dictionary tables)</span>
<span class="kw">local</span> stats = {hp=<span class="num">100</span>, mp=<span class="num">50</span>, xp=<span class="num">200</span>}
<span class="kw">for</span> key, val <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="fn">pairs</span>(stats) <span class="kw">do</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(key .. <span class="str">": "</span> .. val)
<span class="kw">end</span>

<span class="cm">-- While loop (condition checked before each run)</span>
<span class="kw">local</span> lives = <span class="num">3</span>
<span class="kw">while</span> lives &gt; <span class="num">0</span> <span class="kw">do</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(<span class="str">"Lives: "</span> .. lives)
    lives = lives - <span class="num">1</span>
<span class="kw">end</span>

<span class="cm">-- Repeat-until (condition checked AFTER run — always runs once)</span>
<span class="kw">local</span> roll = <span class="num">0</span>
<span class="kw">repeat</span>
    roll = math.<span class="fn">random</span>(<span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">6</span>)
    <span class="rb">print</span>(<span class="str">"Rolled: "</span> .. roll)
<span class="kw">until</span> roll == <span class="num">6</span>   <span class="cm">-- stop when we get a 6</span>

<span class="cm">-- Break — exit any loop immediately</span>
<span class="kw">for</span> i = <span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">100</span> <span class="kw">do</span>
    <span class="kw">if</span> i == <span class="num">5</span> <span class="kw">then</span>
        <span class="kw">break</span>   <span class="cm">-- stop at 5</span>
    <span class="kw">end</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(i)
<span class="kw">end</span></pre>

  <div class="rb-box">🟦 <strong>Roblox warning:</strong> Never use <code>while true do</code> without a <code>task.wait()</code> or delay inside. An empty while true loop FREEZES Roblox Studio! Always add at least <code>task.wait()</code>.</div>
</div>

${Q([
  {q:"In Lua, <code>for i = 1, 5 do</code> runs how many times?",opts:["4","5","6","1"],ans:1,explain:"The loop runs for i = 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 — that's 5 iterations. Both the start and end values are inclusive in Lua's numeric for loop."},
  {q:"Which loop in Lua always runs at least once?",opts:["for","while","repeat-until","All of them"],ans:2,explain:"repeat-until checks the condition AFTER running the body, so it always executes at least once. while checks before, so it might not run at all."},
  {q:"How do you exit a loop early in Lua?",opts:["exit","continue","break","return"],ans:2,explain:"break exits the innermost loop immediately. There is no 'continue' in Lua — you have to restructure the code or use a nested if."},
  {q:"You want to loop over array table <code>t</code> with both index and value. Which is correct?",opts:["for k, v in pairs(t) do","for i, v in ipairs(t) do","for i = 0, #t do","for each v in t do"],ans:1,explain:"ipairs() is designed for sequential array tables — it gives (index, value) pairs starting from 1. pairs() works too but doesn't guarantee order."},
  {q:"What step value would you use to count DOWN from 10 to 1?",opts:["step -1","for i = 10, 1","for i = 10, 1, -1","for i = 1, 10, -1"],ans:2,explain:"The third argument to a numeric for loop is the step. 'for i = 10, 1, -1' counts 10, 9, 8...1. The step must be negative when counting down."},
  {q:"In Roblox, why must you add <code>task.wait()</code> inside a <code>while true do</code> loop?",opts:["To make it run faster","Without it, the loop freezes the game engine — task.wait() yields control back","To avoid memory leaks","It's optional but good practice"],ans:1,explain:"An infinite loop with no yields (task.wait, wait) never gives Roblox time to process other things — it locks up the engine. task.wait() pauses the loop for one frame, keeping the game responsive."},
])}

${FIB("Complete the countdown and spawn loop:",
`<span class="cm">-- Countdown from 10 to 1</span>
<span class="kw">for</span> i = ${blank('10',3)}, <span class="num">1</span>, ${blank('-1',3)} <span class="kw">do</span>
    <span class="rb">print</span>(<span class="str">"Starting in: "</span> .. i)
    task.${blank('wait',5)}(<span class="num">1</span>)
<span class="kw">end</span>
<span class="rb">print</span>(<span class="str">"GO!"</span>)

<span class="cm">-- Safe infinite spawn loop</span>
<span class="kw">while</span> ${blank('true',5)} <span class="kw">do</span>
    spawnEnemy()
    task.${blank('wait',5)}(<span class="num">3</span>)   <span class="cm">-- wait 3 seconds between spawns</span>
<span class="kw">end</span>

<span class="cm">-- Loop with break</span>
<span class="kw">for</span> i = <span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">100</span> <span class="kw">do</span>
    <span class="kw">if</span> i * i > <span class="num">50</span> <span class="kw">then</span>
        ${blank('break',6)}
    <span class="kw">end</span>
<span class="kw">end</span>`,
['10','-1','wait','true','wait','break'])}

${BUG("This loop should print numbers 1 through 5 but crashes Roblox. Find the bug:",
`local i = 1
while i <= 5 do
    print(i)
end`,
["The condition should be <code>i < 5</code>","<code>i</code> is never incremented inside the loop — it loops forever","<code>while</code> should be <code>repeat</code>","<code>print</code> should be <code>warn</code>"],1,
"The loop checks i <= 5 (true) then prints, but never changes i — it stays 1 forever, creating an infinite loop. Fix: add i = i + 1 inside the loop. (Also add task.wait() in Roblox!)")}

${CHALLENGES([
  "Print the times table for 7 (7x1=7 through 7x12=84) using a numeric for loop.",
  "Use a while loop with task.wait() to create a 30-second game timer that prints remaining time.",
  "Loop over a table of 5 enemy names and print only those that start with 'G' using string.sub.",
  "Use repeat-until to simulate rolling dice until you roll doubles (two 6-sided dice with same value).",
  "Loop over a numbers table and print the sum, min, and max without using table library functions.",
])}
`},

